article.headline: Rutgers 79, N. Dakota St. 67
article.story: PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- North Dakota State had skill, desire and composure, but it didn't have enough players to survive a deeper Rutgers team. J.R. Inman had 21 points and 11 rebounds and Rutgers used a late 8-0 run to pull away from stubborn NDSU and take a 79-67 victory in the Blue Ribbon Challenge Sunday. "Coming out at halftime we had a small lead, but I just huddled everyone together and said we needed to pick up the intensity even more and get buckets down the stretch. I think we wore them down at the end of the game, that was why we won," Inman said. Anthony Farmer scored 17 for Rutgers (2-0) and Corey Chandler added 14 points, five assists and three steals. NDSU (0-2), a member of the newly-formed Summit League, gave its second straight foe from a major conference a tough game thanks to 24 points and seven assists from Ben Woodside and 18 points and 11 rebounds from Brett Winkelman. In the Bison's first two games, the starters have scored all but two points, which came from Austin Pennick with 8:56 left against the Scarlet Knights. "That team plays with a lot of pride," Inman said. "They know they may be limited in terms of size and athletic ability, but they play as a team, and they play hard. They can shoot the ball." With the scored tied at 61-61 and 4:05 remaining, Courtney Nelson hit a three-pointer to give Rutgers the lead for good. Inman made one of two foul shots and Farmer and Chandler followed with jumpers to provide a 69-61 advantage with 2:08 remaining. The Bison never got closer than six, as the Scarlet Knights went 6-for-6 from the foul line in the final 52 seconds. "I just think it was our mental toughness," Rutgers coach Fred Hill said of his team's effort in the last five minutes. "The last five minutes we really executed, we were tough." There were six lead changes and five ties in the first 11 minutes of the second half before Rutgers appeared to take control with six straight points to make it 58-52. NDSU, which played Florida tough in its opener, battled back to tie it at 61 before Rutgers went on its decisive run. "In the middle of the second half they kind of scored a little too easy. The last five minutes we really defended, rebounded, executed, made free throws, passed the ball," Hill said. Rutgers spent most of the game's first 13 minutes either tied or trailing before Jaron Griffin's three-pointer began an 8-0 run that gave the Knights a 19-15 lead. Rutgers took two seven-point leads before NDSU cut it to 30-27 at halftime. Both teams shot under 40 percent during the half. NDSU is in its final season becoming eligible for Division I.
